Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the @rosemary{1/2}(leaves picked from stalks and finely chopped) (discard the stalks). Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}. Trim the @courgette{1}, then use a #vegetable peeler{} to peel long ribbons along the length of half the courgette. Quarter the remaining half lengthways and chop widthways into small pieces. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{2} in a #large frying pan{} over high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} and half the rosemary, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, stir-fry until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once coloured, pop the chicken into a #bowl{} and set to one side. 

> We'll finish cooking the chicken later!

Add a glug of oil to the #frying pan{} and return to medium heat. Stir in the onion and a good pinch of @sugar{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until soft and sticky, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once your onions are soft, increase the heat slightly and add the chopped courgette. Cook until starting to colour, ~{4-5%minutes}, then add the garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Pour in the @water{150%ml} for the sauce, @chicken stock powder{1}, @crème fraîche{112.5%g} and a knob of @?butter{}. Return the chicken to the pan and simmer until cooked, ~{7-8%minutes}. 

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle!

Add the courgette ribbons for the final ~{2%minutes}.

While the sauce is cooking, pour the boiled water from the kettle into a #large saucepan{} over high heat. Bring back to the boil then add @salt{0.5%tsp} and the @spaghetti{200%g}. Cook until tender, ~{8%minutes}, then drain in a #sieve{} (save a little of the pasta water to loosen up the sauce later on!). Return the pasta to the now empty #saucepan{} off the heat, drizzle over a little olive oil and stir through to stop the pasta from sticking together.

Meanwhile, pop the lemon zest, remaining rosemary and olive oil into a small bowl. Mix together then season with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Once the chicken has cooked and the sauce has thickened, stir in the cheddar and add the drained spaghetti to the pan. Toss to coat in the sauce. Cook until piping hot. 

> Add a splash of pasta water if the sauce is too thick!

To finish, add a squeeze of lemon juice to the pasta. Taste and season well with salt and lots of pepper. Add a little more lemon juice if needed. Divide the spaghetti between your bowls and spoon over the rosemary drizzle. Enjoy!